
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `hexdump` baraye namayesh dade-haye binary dar yek format hexadesimal (base 16) va ASCII estefade mishavad. In dastoor bishtar baraye didan va tahlil kardan file-haye binary ke ghabele khandan nistand be kar miravad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `hexdump -C filename`  --> 🗂️ Namayesh file be soorate canonical (ham hex va ham ASCII)
    🔹 `hexdump -n length filename`  --> ✂️ Faghat `length` byte az file ra namayesh midahad.
    🔹 `hexdump -v filename`  --> 👓 Namayesh hameye dade-ha, hatta agar yeksan bashand (pooshesh ra hazf mikonad).

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ hexdump file.bin

    🔹 Namayesh file.bin be soorate hexadesimal.

    $ hexdump -C file.bin

    🔹 Namayesh file.bin be soorate hex va ASCII dar kenar ham.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ hexdump -n 16 file.bin

    🔹 Faghat 16 byte aval file.bin ra namayesh midahad. In baraye check kardane maghadire avalie yek file binary mofid ast.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `hexdump` command is used to display binary data in a hexadecimal (base 16) and ASCII format. This command is commonly used to view and analyze binary files that are not human-readable.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `hexdump -C filename`  --> 🗂️ Display the file in a canonical format (both hex and ASCII).
    🔹 `hexdump -n length filename`  --> ✂️ Display only the first `length` bytes of the file.
    🔹 `hexdump -v filename`  --> 👓 Display all data, even if identical (suppresses compression of identical lines).

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ hexdump file.bin

    🔹 Display file.bin in hexadecimal format.

    $ hexdump -C file.bin

    🔹 Display file.bin in hex and ASCII side-by-side.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ hexdump -n 16 file.bin

    🔹 Display only the first 16 bytes of file.bin. This is useful for checking the initial values of a binary file.
